article.description: Ahead by 17 early in the first half, the L.A. Sparks beat the host Houston Comets 69-59 Saturday in a game that featured technicals against Lisa Leslie and Sheryl Swoopes.
article.headline: L.A. comfortably ahead before Olympians square off
article.linkText: Swoopes, Leslie get into tiff as Sparks win at Houston
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- By the time the two Olympians traded shoves, Los
Angeles already had a big lead on Houston.

Ahead by 17 early in the first half, the Sparks beat the Comets
69-59 Saturday in a game that featured technicals against Lisa
Leslie and Sheryl Swoopes.

Tamika Whitmore had 20 points and Chamique Holdsclaw added 15
points for Los Angeles (11-9), which also beat the Comets 83-64 on
June 15.

Houston trailed 66-52 after Swoopes' layup with 5:30 left. She
then bumped Leslie under the basket, and Leslie responded by
shoving Swoopes in the back.

"I think it was just a heated moment," Leslie said. "When
Sheryl went to the basket, she scored and pushed me. It was just a
reaction when she pushed me."

Swoopes said she was not going to back down from Leslie, her
Olympic partner on three gold-medal winning teams.

"I think she gets to the point where she feels like she can do
whatever and nobody is going to do or say anything about it,"
Swoopes said. "When the referee didn't take control of it when it
happened, I'm not going to back down, so I retaliated."

Teammates had to keep the players separated.

Holdsclaw, the WNBA's leading scorer, had 10 points in the
second half. She said the win, the first of eight straight road
games, should help with the rest of the trip.

"There was a lot of emotion out there today, and I think it was
good for us to come out here and play as a team to get this win,"
Holdsclaw said. "We made a lot of adjustments and I though we
handled everything the way we needed to."

Swoopes had 17 points for the Comets (12-9), who have lost two
straight at home after beating the Western Conference-leading
Sacramento Monarchs on Tuesday.

Swoopes made 7-of-19 shots for the Comets, who have lost four
straight to the Sparks.

"We got off to a slow start and when you play a team as good as
L.A., you can't recover," Swoopes said. "You can't afford to dig
yourself into a hole like that. It's very disappointing."

Leslie and Mwadi Mabika had 11 points each for the Sparks.
Leslie added 10 rebounds.

The Comets started the second half with a 7-4 run to get within
44-39, but Whitmore scored eight quick points to get the lead back
to 10 with 13:25 to go.

"Whitmore just killed us," said Houston coach Van Chancellor.
"She jumped on us and we didn't guard her from start to finish. I
would say that was probably one of the poorest jobs of ever
guarding a player."

The Sparks took a 31-14 lead in the first 14 minutes of the game
behind eight points from Whitmore.

Mabika gave the Sparks a seven-point lead with an easy basket
before the Comets rallied to get to 40-32 at the break. Tina
Thompson made a layup to start the run with 4:21 left and then hit
a long 3-pointer to cap Houston's 18-9 spurt to end the half.

Thompson, in her second game back since maternity leave,
finished with nine points on 4-of-9 shooting.

The Comets made just five of their first 19 shots from the
floor, but made 9-of-11 after the drought.
